<rss xmlns:taxo="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/taxonomy/" xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" version="2.0">
  <channel>
    <title>Summit report from a Cleric's perspective</title>
    <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8524</link>
    <description>Sorry for the delay, between lost luggage, a busy week at work, and Father's Day, I haven't had time to focus on my notes until now. I'll try to get as much as I can into this report as they pertain to Clerics.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The Summit and Fan Faire was set up as follows:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;On Wednesday, most of us arrived at the Hotel and had free time. We gathered at the bar outside Quarks for a quick introduction and get to know eachother and stuff like that.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;On Thursday was the Summit. We were separated in Meelee and Caster groups with the Hybrids having their choice as to where they go. There were 4 1 hour sessions through the day 2 in the morning, 2 in the afternoon, with 30 minutes between them and an hour break for lunch. The sessions had general themes to them. For me they ended up being:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Session 1: Live discussion. Discussion of the game in general as it is now; where it is going in the near future, how it is now.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Session 2: Class discussion: Issues particular to classes.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Session 3: Future discussion: Discussion of the future of the game, where it is going, what's coming up.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Session 4: Open forem: Talk about anything that may have been missed in the previous discussions.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Between sessions and at the lunch and dinners, there were lots of opportunities to talk with the SOE people about anything.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;On Friday, the Fan Faire started. Over Friday and Saturday, there were numerous open forums for anyone to attend and ask related questions. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I attended the following forums:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;- Customer Service Forum: Talk about the CS situation in general in EQ.&lt;br&gt;- Progressions of Powers forums: Talk about AA's, Disciplines, Spells,Items, etc....&lt;br&gt;- EQ/EQII Community discussion: Talk about the EQLive boards, and with the mods.&lt;br&gt;- Maintaining a living world (I missed a chunk of this one for the Expansion preview)&lt;br&gt;- Everquest Technology Discussion: (Showing off some of the framework of EQ, particularly pathing and lighting)&lt;br&gt;- Everquest Tradeskill Discussion.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;In my opinion, the Summit discussions tended to dig into a topic deeper, whereas the Fan Faire forums tended to be thouched on lightly and then the next topic was brought up. That meant that the Summit discussions had less overall topics but we got into more details, whereas the Fan Faire forums had more touched on at least.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I will try to keep this to Cleric-related issues only, based on what I heard and could ask. These are mostly going in the order of my notes, and some items may be repeated. I am going to try and give as much detail as I can with them.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;One question brought up was the issue about the number of clerics on raids. This is a major balancing issue since it is hard to design encounters where more healers does not make the encounter easier. It is an on going issue that will be constantly looked at as encounters are made and rebalanced; but in general they can not beat human nature. And human nature is basically saying "If I bring 2x clerics to this encounter, it becomes 2x easier." &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I brought up the issue of cleric DPS in general, no real specifics. The topic itself had to be tabled however until more of the reenvisionning improvements come through. The guy who was crunching all the DPS numbers was not at the summit, and those that were there did not want to say anything that would probably be changed later anyways.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;An issue about botting in general was brought up. The Devs are not happy with the KEI/Virtue botting you see in PoK. They brainstormed (Note this is NOT being implemented; it's still very much in the 'well what if we did this?' stage) the idea of buffs fading if the buffer was not in the group. We at the summit really did NOT like that idea; but we did toss out a counter idea. The idea that while grouped, the buff timers are effectively frozen; but if you leave the group the (much reduced) timers start going down; to give a group enough time to find a suitable replacement. A lot of notes were taken, but this won't be something we will see soon, one way or another.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The Mage summoned invis stones being lore was brought up. The Devs are against making them un-lore because they do NOT want to see them in the Bazaar. They were very adamant about that issue as well, so I don't feel we'll get much movement on that issue. (I'd love to see those stones non-lore myself)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;As for invis in general, the Dev's did say that they have finally fixed the underlying coding issues that prevented 1-charge items from stacking. So we will see Cloudy Potions (and similar potions) stackable soon.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;They are also increasing the drop rates for the components of the Alchemy improved invis potions. I wasn't in that discussion but it may just be that the items will have a higher chance to drop off mobs and/or appear in chests, but they are still limited to Guk LDoN's. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;We asked if the short duration buffs could be moved to the short duration window. The Dev laughed and commented about how he gets asked that once a week and said it was a no go. He didn't go into details about WHY it is a no go however.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I managed to corner Rytan briefly, and asked if there was a chance we could lower the chance of procs breaking roots. He told me that it would not be possible due to the way roots and spells are coded at the moment. Later on, I asked if the Strong Root AA that druids and wizards get could be expanded to other classes. There was some nodding of heads from the Dev's and lots of note taking but no firm "yes" or "No" about it coming our way. I suspect it is, at the very least, on their sheets for further discussion.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;A switch to turn armor helms on and off was asked about. The Dev's said they know how they can do it, and that it would be relatively easy to do (2-3 days of work), it is just low on the priority list. As for adding more visible armor sets in general, that is not likely to happen until they take care of the PC Models. There just isn't much room in general for more armors, or much else. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I did ask about making more robes available, and got a firm "We'll see about it." from the Devs. They seemed surprised that some clerics didn't want to wear plate. They did make clear that if robes were CLR useable, they would have less AC then plate, but that's a given anyways.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I also asked Vahlar and a few other Dev's about the cleric diety quest line. She knew that some of those spells existed, like the Dark Elf snare necklace and the Brell beer necklace, but she wasn't aware that there were many of those. She seemed very open towards expanding those lines and filling in the missing ones.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;For the number crunchers in our midst, the practice test dummies will eventually go live. The Dev's like them, but there are a few minor details holding them back from releasing the dummies live. There is no ETA on this besides "eventually". (One issue mentionned was to make sure that the numbers people gather are right and can not be griefed or confused by other people using the dummies.)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;For the group leaders in our midst, there was discussions about sharing the Leadership abilities in a raid and group among the leaders better. That means that someone other than the leader may earn Leader XP, or someone could be leader to earn the points, but someone else's abilities are in effect. There was a lot of interest from all sides about that in general, so I am very hopeful something will come from that.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;This is going live with the next patch, but the /assist group and /assist raid ranges are being expanded  to use the same range as /assist in general. The devs are also open to increasing the range within reason as well, though I haven't seen much discussion since then as to what the range will be. After the patch next week, the range should be double checked to see what we might want it to be.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The idea of "Health of Target's Target's Target" and Group HoTT Leadership skills were brought up. HoT^3 was laughed at, but there was a lot of interest in them. I suspect seeds have been planted, and I urge people to keep mentionning them if you would like to see them.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;"Loot All" for our own corpses was discussed and turned down. The Devs feel that it is a game philosophy issue (Son of The Vision), and it is extremely unlikely to ever happen. Not that it will never happen; but don't hold your breath waiting for it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;On the other hand, speaking about corpses, the Dev's mentionned an idea I really liked about PC corpses. They are considering (but this is still in the brainstorming stage, so don't expect it any time soon), a way so that an XP-Rezzable corpse, will not poof  if you loot everything (or loop an empty corpse). They are considering adding a "Destroy corpse" button or something like that which you would have to click to clear the corpse if it could be rezzed. The idea is VERY preliminary, but was very positively received.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Increasing the power of Cleric healing was asked at one point, and it was shot down. The Dev's explained healing in general at that point. Encounters are basically designed around healing power, cleric healing power in particular. The Dev's design the top end encounters of an expansion to push cleric healing to the limits (and even slightly beyond) of the healing available in that expansion (so top Healing AA's, healing augs, healing spells, epics, etc....). Increasing our healing abilities between expansions would mean rebalancing those encounters to match the new abilities. Basically, don't expect any large scale healing changes except when new expansions come out (with new content designed to match the new healing level)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Cleric damage mitigation, and damage handling in general was talked about. The large gap between the tank's ability to handle damage and non-tanks to handle damage was acknowledged. The Devs are working on ways to decrease that gap without necessarily letting other classes tank. What those ways are was not mentionned. The eventual goal would be to reduce the bang-you're-dead effect that a lot of classes get if aggro shifts to them for even a moment.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Wizards brought up this point, but it applies to all of us more or less. The issue with the resist rates on mobs and how they've been more or less constantly going up. The Devs are more or less happy with how things are now, but are open to reducing resists on some mobs, especially the trash-mobs. This will probably be a long term balancing as they tweek with resists over time, and with new content.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Similarly, stuns were also mentionned though not much was said about them. (That discussion dissolved into a brief talk about Lucy instead). But other than resist rates, the Dev's are fairly happy with stuns as they are now. The impression I had, is that Stun is supposed to be more of an interrupter, and not a complete mob stopper, hence why it fades off of mobs in a tick or so.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Mana and Endurance regen rates, especially outside of combat, were touched on briefly. The Dev's admitted that with the large pools available today, the downtime waiting for mana and endurance to regen outside of battle is becoming prohibitive. Methods not told to us are being tossed around internally to improve that situation.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Talking about Endurance, this may or may not affect us, but it may eventually. When stamina was changed to Endurance, the Devs said that Endurance regen rates were designed with max regen rates already in place. They didn't want Meelee's to be dependant on a buff. With the increased use of Disciplines, and Endurance pools as big as they are now, the Dev's are considering some Endurance regen improvers. There is a slight chance that it will be in the form of spells, but more likely it will be an equivalent to Flowing Thought items.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Finally, I managed to catch some Dev's (sadly Rytan was not among them) to talk about the Hammers and Yaulps.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I mentionned how our summoned hammer line has rather large gaps both in availibility and the procs. Those devs were very interested and would be willing to bring it up internally.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I also talked about the mana regen on the Yaulp line. They countered that mana regen rates in the lower levels are fine as far as they are concerned due to the strength of the Meditate skill. I reminded them that yaulp fades while sitting, so meditate doesn't really apply there. They were surprised by that and said they would look into it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Well, just as an addendum to that, I checked out the lower yaulps and was surprised. Yaulp 1-4 (the ones without Regen) do NOT fade when sitting. Yaulp's behaviour changes completely between yaulp 4 and 5. I'll be starting a discussion on yaulp later to consider changing those lower level spells to better reflect the upper versions (complete with the fade when sitting). I also noticed that there are some stacking issues among the Yaulps in that they don't always overwrite or block eachother.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Finally, Loral and I were talking with someone about Turn Undead. There is one idea that was brought up that looks like a really nice solution to the Turn Undead issues. The Dev is still checking on the feasibility of it, so I can't give any more details about it until it is announced. It should (baring the issue of the lack of undead content in general) make TU useful for us.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Those are, I believe, all the cleric related issues that I wrote down. There was a LOT discussed over those days, for all classes and the game in general. I found the SOE people were very open to the ideas and issues we raised. The attitude of both the SOE people and the players was very positive and hopeful. Everyone involved seemed to feel that there is an exciting future for EQ.</description>
    <pubDate>Sat, 25 Jun 2005 18:34:29 GMT</pubDate>
