    <item>
      <title>Re: Summit report from a Cleric's perspective</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8826#M8826</link>
      <description>&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
GlowingRune wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Seems like the current incarnation of EQ has essentially stated that past a certain amount of protection from armor, one's combat&amp;nbsp;experience&amp;nbsp;(as estimated&amp;nbsp;by one's&amp;nbsp;character class) is a more important factor in deciding how much damage one takes from a hit than is one's armor.&amp;nbsp; Several people here disagree with that approach and call it outrageous, or intolerable, or unreasonable, or whatever.&amp;nbsp; But in an abstract sense, it's just as defensible as going the other way and stating that the kind of armor you're wearing should be the dominating factor and that only explicit combat skills like defense/block/parry/dodge should make a distinction between the amount of damage a priest takes versus a tank.&amp;nbsp; Folks may disagree with it (in fact I somewhat disagree with it myself), but I think it's absurd to reference other game systems and try to claim the the current status quo is unreasonable in some way because it doesn't seem "realistic" or in line with some other irrelevent game.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;The way things work now is perfectly reasonable, perfectly self consistent, and can be easily justified using a logical set of assumptions.&amp;nbsp; Personally, I think&amp;nbsp;the artifically low class based soft caps&amp;nbsp;screw up game and class balance at the high end the way things are now, so I object to it on those principles.&amp;nbsp; But I think anyone objecting to the current status quo based on analogies to D&amp;amp;D or some "plate should&amp;nbsp;mitigate like&amp;nbsp;plate" nonsense is just looking to justify something they want in entirely the wrong way.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I still think making a request for an increased AC return over the soft cap for everyone would help plate classes the most and move them more toward the mitigation advantage they expect.&amp;nbsp; And it's easily justified by a number of arguments, none of which involve D&amp;amp;D or (imho) incorrect assumptions regarding the nature or plate armor.&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I think you and the others in this thread, agree on general principle, but seem to disagree on justification. Bottom line however, is that softcaps don't make any kind of sense. If clerics were not supposed to get to 2500ac, then why not fix the problem by itemizing cleric armor differently, or by giving a smaller bonus to worn ac than they have now.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;If I recall correctly, plate tanks get something like 2.0 actual ac from 1 worn ac on an item. Clerics get something like 1.3 AC per item ac. Robe classes get 1.0? This difference reflects any battle training or experience that might be used as justification for differential effects of armor. Seems perfectly reasonable. Then on TOP of that, they throw in softcaps. Hmm, I upgrade from a 51 ac bp, to a 65 ac bp, and based on my skill and training, get 1.3 times the base ac. Later, I upgrade from a 72ac bp, to a 96ac bp, and get 0.33 worn ac per base ac, just because I have better armor in my other slots. Did I forget how to use a breastplate? &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Basically, IMHO, softcaps are lazy coding. If I am not supposed to have 2100ac buffed, then put less than 96ac on my BP. Or reduce the AC multiplier to 1.1. To have ac work up to a certain point, then stop working, is ridiculous.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I seriously doubt that giving me the full benefit of all my worn ac, would somehow be unbalancing, or make clerics viable tanks. All it might do is let me survive long enough to get my DA spell cast.&lt;/P&gt;</description>
