    <item>
      <title>Re: Summit report from a Cleric's perspective</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8732#M8732</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;There are several parts to the Ac equation. &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;First, the softcap. Past the softcap, I get very little benefit to ac. I have 2100 ac buffed atm. Other than resists, mana and better focuses, I have no reason to upgrade gear, because I stopped getting a significant benefit from ac a long time ago. My vote would be to remove ALL softcaps on ac, for ALL classes. AC is AC. If Sony doesn't like their own itemization, creating artificial "softcaps" is a poor fix.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Second, there is the return per worn ac. If i recall correctly, cloth classes get 1 point of worn ac, per listed ac on the&amp;nbsp;item, and that scales up, with tanks getting the highest return. This makes sense. A trained warrior should be able to get better use out of a breastplate, due to his superior battle training. Clerics get priest ac returns. Higher than robe casters, but lower than everyone else. This alone should be the penalty we pay, not an additional softacp.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Third, there are the avoidance/mitigation skills. Dodge, block, parry etc. Melees get more of these, as would be expected. They are trained in battle, not magic or healing. Right now, this difference makes a 1200ac warrior take a LOT less damage than a 1200ac cleric. That's below the softcap, and at that level, it works. However, once the softcap is hit, then all the extra ac means diddly. If my 2100 ac all counted, I'd still take a heck of a lot more damage, because my dodge cap is low, and I have no other avoidance techniques, but to treat me like I only had 1500ac, is downright insulting.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I'm a fairly conventional cleric.&amp;nbsp;I don't try to solo very often (although I did have fun soloing those Akheva mobs for my epic 1.5 drop, dark blues at that). I'd just like to have a bit better chance of surviving long enough to back away or get DA off, when the mob decides to summon me. &lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Sun, 17 Jul 2005 21:18:07 GMT</pubDate>
      <author>Treeslayer</author>
      <guid>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8732#M8732</guid>
      <dc:creator>Treeslayer</dc:creator>
      <dc:date>2005-07-17T21:18:07Z</dc:date>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Re: Summit report from a Cleric's perspective</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8690#M8690</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;I'm starting to think that the issue here is really one of the return over the soft cap moreso than the cap itself.&amp;nbsp; As GlowingRune pointed out, plate armour inherently has more AC than chain, leather or silk.&amp;nbsp; The problem is that since our returns over the soft cap are so crappy, the higher inherent AC is essentially worthless.&amp;nbsp; If the return over the soft cap was increased (and I don't necessarily&amp;nbsp;mean just for clerics) then the fact that we have higher AC, on average, would again have some meaning - i.e. we would mitigate better.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;That's not to say that the soft cap is not important too...&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Kaalen&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
