    <item>
      <title>Re: Summit report from a Cleric's perspective</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8691#M8691</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
kaalen wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I'm starting to think that the issue here is really one of the return over the soft cap moreso than the cap itself.&amp;nbsp; As GlowingRune pointed out, plate armour inherently has more AC than chain, leather or silk.&amp;nbsp; The problem is that since our returns over the soft cap are so crappy, the higher inherent AC is essentially worthless.&amp;nbsp; If the return over the soft cap was increased (and I don't necessarily&amp;nbsp;mean just for clerics) then the fact that we have higher AC, on average, would again have some meaning - i.e. we would mitigate better.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;That's not to say that the soft cap is not important too...&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Kaalen&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Eliminating the soft cap entirely would presumably mean that your AC scales as you'd expect.&amp;nbsp; Upping the return&amp;nbsp;on&amp;nbsp;AC over&amp;nbsp;the soft cap would help a bit less, essentially reducing the damping of the curve, but would still help.&amp;nbsp; It might be easier to convince the devs to do the latter change since it would have less impact and presumably less chance of causing unexpected balance shifts.&amp;nbsp; They want to avoid a situation like we had in the past where monks were better tanks than tank classes.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Regarding Hurk's D&amp;amp;D analogy:&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;That's all very interesting stuff, but in my opinion has little to no relevance.&amp;nbsp; EQ is only based in the most superficial ways on D&amp;amp;D and in my opinion, it's a real reach to try to make game balance decisions based on how close EQ follows D&amp;amp;D.&amp;nbsp; Based on what's actually in EQ, "plate mitigation" = "higher ac on plate armor".&amp;nbsp; As far as I am aware, there has never been any other special property of plate armor that makes it have hidden mitigation bonuses, nor is there any basis (in EQ)&amp;nbsp;for thinking there should be.&amp;nbsp; Nor should we be adding another hidden property that we have to make guesses about.&amp;nbsp; AC is listed on the armor.&amp;nbsp; Plate armor has higher AC already.&amp;nbsp; If AC worked as we expect, there'd be no discussion about this topic.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;It's not like&amp;nbsp;armor says "plate armor" on its stats (like WoW).&amp;nbsp; In fact, shamans (theoretically a chain class) can wear various armor that looks a whole lot like plate, so even who can wear what kind of armor is more tied to class than some notion of "plate class" versus "chain class".&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The way I read a lot of the demands for plate mitigation is that a few outspoken clerics really wanted to have paladins and have melee envy.&amp;nbsp; If these outspoken clerics phrased their requests properly and stopped asking to migitate damage the same as plate tanks and instead asked that the AC soft cap be raised or the return over it be raised, then that perception would go away and you might actually find some support among end-game players of other classes.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by GlowingRune on &lt;span class=date_text&gt;07-07-2005&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=time_text&gt;11:54 AM&lt;/span&gt;</description>
